text.tspan: Is the mean number of storms different,
depending on the El Nino type?
In some years unusually warm ocean
currents occur in the Pacific around
These 'El Nino' years are thought to result
in extreme climate in the Western Pacific.
There is very strong evidence that the mean number of storms is
related to the El Nino pattern – there would be only a 0.2% probability of
such a large F ratio even if there was no difference.
The annual number of storms from 1950
to 1995 are shown on the right.
